{"id": "15331", "revid": "46586549", "url": "https://wowpedia.fandom.com/wiki?curid=15331", "title": "Scorpid", "text": "The scorpid are gigantic creatures similar to &lt;a href=\"scorpion\"&gt;scorpion&lt;/a&gt;s and &lt;a href=\"arachnathid\"&gt;arachnathid&lt;/a&gt;. They measure an average of 3 ft. long.\nThey attack anything they perceive as a threat with their claws and stinger, which holds venom capable of killing creatures up to 100 times its own body weight. When stung, the venom causes rapid suffocation followed by violent seizures, and shortly after, death. Although tail venom of most scorpids is the most deadly, it is the bite of the diminutive &lt;a href=\"scorpling\"&gt;scorpling&lt;/a&gt; that is the greatest threat. &lt;a href=\"Stonelash%20Pincer\"&gt;Some species&lt;/a&gt; also have venomous pincers. Hunting and killing scorpid is considered a rite of passage by the orcs. \nScorpids speak in complex clicking and chittering sounds, which sentient beings can actually learn and communicate with, such as &lt;a href=\"Zathra\"&gt;Zathra&lt;/a&gt;.\n\"Cataclysm\" introduced a second model for scorpids, which is used by some of the new scorpid and &lt;a href=\"scorpion\"&gt;scorpion&lt;/a&gt; mobs.\nKnown scorpids.\nExtinct scorpids.\nSince the cataclysm, the following species of scorpid have disappeared from the game, presumably having gone extinct.\nSilithid scorpids.\nIn addition, several scorpids, or scorpid-like creatures are found amongst the &lt;a href=\"silithid\"&gt;silithid&lt;/a&gt;. It is possible that other species of scorpid also worked for the silithid.\nAs a mount.\nSince &lt;a href=\"Patch%204.0.3a\"&gt;Patch 4.0.3a&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"Reins%20of%20the%20Kor%27kron%20Annihilator\"&gt;Reins of the Kor'kron Annihilator&lt;/a&gt; is sold to players for after completing the achievement &lt;a href=\"Guild%20Level%2025%20%28Horde%29\"&gt;Guild Level 25 (Horde)&lt;/a&gt;. The reins use the second model of Scorpid.\nIn the RPG.\nScorpid young routinely molt, shedding their old, soft skin and growing a harder carapace in its place. Scorpids molt 5 to 6 times before reaching maturity. Cautious travelers watch for shed scorpid skins when traveling in the desert."}
